the “discovery” of Costa Rica by Americans. Especially this year is a big deal because it is the 10 Year Anniversary since the opening of the CIMA I.C, which is the first facility of this kind in Central America. This has led to more attention in the International medical field, flight corporations assisting with direct flights to Costa Rica, and in general the country being perceived in a much more positive way than in the past.

Generally speaking, most Costa Ricans aren’t very happy with the state of the country at this time (there is no real system of government in place just yet), they may still be living in fear from years gone by, but they still love the country and wouldn’t live anywhere else. Poverty is still a huge issue here, as well as F.U.N. Fifteen year-old kids partying, drinking, smoking pot, making their own music videos, driving their cars like reckless barn animals, wearing their baggy clothes, piercing everything imaginable, and of course fighting. This is a terrifyingly regular occurrence that most tourists are not exposed to, but should be aware of. The media portrays this as if it is a very high risk for danger, with the youth randomly shot down just in the middle of the streets. This could not be farther from the truth though. The youth is a very important part of this revolution and many of the best of these youths are paved away for greater good by doing special missions in other countries where there is international danger.
